This paper discusses the use of machine learning algorithms to balance competing objectives, which is a common topic in the field of machine learning (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of noisy data and the trade-offs between private and public objectives, which are relevant to the fields of artificial intelligence (cs.AI) and data science (cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of fairness-constrained profit-maximizing policies, which is relevant to the field of computational economics (cs.CE). Finally, the paper discusses the applicability of the approach to a wide range of practical decisions, which is relevant to the field of social informatics (cs.SI).
